00:01:58.170 --> 00:01:59.320
is so much fun.

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:02.560
In Zombieland, the
challenge was really

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:04.680
about bridging design
and filmmaking.

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:06.370
It was directed by
Ruben Fleischer.

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:09.180
And he was taking an
approach that we understood

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:12.300
in terms of bringing
type into the film

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:14.140
in a real integrated way.

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:17.510
We were responsible
for the whole intro.

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:21.640
So the whole beginning required
a lot of design thinking.

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:24.320
Eventually everything
clicked that this

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:28.590
was going to be these beautiful
slow motion shots of zombies

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:31.720
all around the country killing
people and then integrating

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:34.720
the type in the
same way, so having

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:37.790
them move in that
beautiful balletic style.

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:40.840
So you have this grace to
it, and at the same time

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:42.280
it's horrific.

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:44.070
I think from the
beginning Ruben also

00:02:44.070 --> 00:02:47.700
wanted to have the rules
be typographically featured

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:48.450
within the film.

00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:52.400
So the solution for that was
to have the type interact

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:55.320
and be part of the scene, and so
in a sense become a character.

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:58.020
What we really discovered
is that we didn't

00:02:58.020 --> 00:02:59.282
want to overpower the image.

00:02:59.282 --> 00:03:00.490
The images were so fantastic.

00:03:00.490 --> 00:03:03.230
And so we didn't want
to have the font do

00:03:03.230 --> 00:03:05.640
so much of that work, and
say, like, hey, I'm funny,

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:06.610
I'm a funny font.

00:03:06.610 --> 00:03:07.650
It didn't need that.

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:09.740
It didn't need to be sort
of slapped in your face.

00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:13.820
I remember seeing it in the
theater and people laughing

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:15.240
at the way that
the type behaved.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:17.160
That was just a really
gratifying moment,

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:21.907
to see that type could
entertain in that way.

00:03:21.907 --> 00:03:23.740
JIM HELTON: I've always
loved title designs.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:24.970
I've always loved title making.

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:26.553
